children.subject:
Is EE123's workload that high? I thought it would be as difficult as a "moderate" EECS tech like 161 or 186. I've been told that 126 earned a reputation for being the hardest undergrad EECS class on campus, but I haven't heard anything about 123 being extremely high workload.

Given that, if you had to choose 1 between 123 and 126 for someone interested in communications and control, which would be more useful? I'm pretty set on doing 189 at the moment.

For me, yes, 123's workload was that high. I can't gauge how much of that was just me versus how hard the class actually is though; some people I've talked to spent closer to 10 hours a week, although I've talked to yet other people I took it with who said the numbers I listed above were consistent with their experience as well. Don't let that discourage you from taking it though - it's a very rewarding class that shows you a lot of interesting extensions and applications of 120 content and Miki is a fantastic teacher who's as enthusiastic about the subject matter as is humanly possible. 

As for choosing only 1 for comm/control, that's a tough one. My general attitude is to go with the more "fundamental" class (126), but 123's labs are entirely structured around hands-on Ham radio communication, so there's probably a lot of value to you in those. I don't think either is a bad choice if you can only pick one. If in your situation, I'd probably pick 126 just because it's harder to self-study.

123 will definitely surprise you if you’re expecting a 120-esque workload - the psets are noticeably harder and the labs are a pretty decent time commitment as well. The final project is fairly intense - I took it at the same time as 151 and it was a nightmare of a last month of the semester. Average hour commitment was something around 12-15 a week for 123 for me.

Haven't taken 189 (from what I've heard, I'll assume it's approximately equal to the other two in terms of difficulty/workload), but 123 and 126 were, to me, the first and second highest workload classes I've taken here, respectively. I took them in different semesters and easily spent 15-20+ hours a week on each (for 123, that number was more like 30+ toward the end with the last few labs and final project; 126 was more consistent in terms of workload). I wouldn't even recommend any two of these together to most people. However, like the student answerer says, you could probably get away with any two of them if you work hard given your track record. But I wouldn't recommend much more than that.

history.content:
If I only took these three classes in 1 semester, could I pull it off? Apparently 189 with Shewchuk is less work than other offerings? I'm about to graduate, but I still want to do well and learn all the content.

I've done 3 UD EECS techs before and gotten all As, but never 3 "hard" UD EECS techs. I would like to still keep my GPA up because I might apply to grad school after working for some time.
history.subject: Are 123, 126 and 189 doable in 1 semester?
